@node "Document_2" "SCELTA VARIE DIRECTORY"
@next "Document_2"
         THE SINTAX CONTROL FOR FILE AUTODOC

This function make a sintax control on every @{b}@{fg shine}*.doc@{ub} text} @{b}file@{ub}@{fg text} into Autodoc
Directory

It write the error in the "@{"control window" link "Document_8" 0}" into the program's main window and
into a XXX.ERR file in the Guide Directory (XXX="name of TOC").


        AUTODOC SINTAX:

Here is @{b}how to write the autodoc file@{ub}:


@{b}@{fg shine}N.B.: The Table of Contents is not obligatory for this version@{ub}@{fg text}

First line (obligatory) TABLE OF CONTENTS,[RET],[RET]
doc_name.category/function1_name [RET] doc_name.category/function2_name [RET]
.... doc_name.category/last_function_name [FF]



doc_name.category/function_name [TAB & or SPACE]

@{b}The double title of function is not obligatory@{ub}

doc_name.category/function_name [RET]

        (follow function's description)

      ......................................

at end description [FF]




@{b}@{i}@{fg shine}The last function is also the End Of File@{ub}@{ui}@{fg shine} shine} text}


@{fg shine}WARNING !! WARNING !!@{b}

Don't append "()" to function name into Table of Contents !!!


This sytem don't accept Function-Name (in descrpitory part) without the prefix
XXX.YYY/@{ub}@{fg text} The suffix "()" anywhere into doc file is interpreted as function's
keyword. You must append that if want link function to amigaguide file

where is

- XXX = name of file

- YYY = category of file (library,device, resource, ecc...)

WITHOUT THAT THE CONTROL WINDOW SHOW:

@{b}- SINTAX ERROR IN DESCRIPTION FUNCTION (without function name !!)@{ub}
@endnode

@node "Document_4" "grassetto"
       
                       @{b}@{fg shine}NEW AUTOGUIDE@{ub}@{fg text}

This is the main function,

It:         1st        -        make sintax control on all autodoc files into
AUTODOC'S DIRECTORY (if error report, then stop function and write XXX.ERR
file & show error into " @{"control window" link "Document_8" 0} ")

        2nd        -         Load & elaborate Guide file from every Autodoc
File

        3rd        -        Ask the icon for TOC file (from Sys:envarc
directory)

The TOC file (choose name of that from Text-gadget) is an general index of
guide file (alfabetically & class sorted) & analytic Index for all functions &
structures (in case of Assembler language, also macro's index). You can choose
Assembler or C & C++ language from @{"OPTIONS" link "Document_5" 0}.

Into this new version the program select category of autodoc file from
description on FD files (You must choose its directory from main window). If
.fd file not exist, this program search into autodoc the category, if not
found, then select OTHER category.
@endnode

@node "Document_5" "sintassi"
         @{b}@{fg shine}OPTIONS@{ub}@{fg text}

        @{b}BOLD WORD@{ub}

Only for amigaguide.library » 39.00 !!!

The listview display the words that will show bold into Guide text.

        @{b}SKIPPED WORDS@{ub}

The listview display the words that don't show into Function's Index of TOC
file (That will show only on Index of Function of single Guide file )


For both, You can choose if change, delete or add new word, with the
text-gadget after listview.


        @{b}LANGUAGE@{ub}

You can choose for C or Assembler language with mx-gagdget


At last, If You choose CANCEL, nothingh will change !!!

If You choose OK, the program create an @{fg shine}AUTOGUIDE.PREFS FILE@{fg text} into SYS:
directory. That is an ASCII file where are the bold words, the skipped &
language (i- assembler or h- C). You can modify this file for change the
option into program (only before start the program)
@endnode

@node "Document_6" "ADD  AUTOGUIDE"

        @{b}@{bg shine} ADD AUTODOC@{ub}@{bg back}


It add new or change old guide file into guide's directory & TOC file.

If the Guide file it's already present, a system requester will ask for change
that file (OK or Cancel option). All new Include & Autodoc file must lie into
same Directory. The program copy the new include files in a  directory named
"OTHER", into the original Include's directory.
@endnode

